<TITLE> Bangladesh 27-2 at tea, England 599-6 dec </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 13 (bdnews24.com)  England struck twice before tea to leave Bangladesh in trouble at 27-2 after they declared their first innings on 599 for six on the second day of the first Test at the Zohur Ahmed Chowdhury Stadium in Chittagong on Saturday. The home side lost opener Imrul Kayes and Junaid Siddique with hardly any significant runs on the board to the bowling of Stuart Broad. Bangladesh lost their first wicket with the score on 13 when Kayes was caught behind for four while Junaid was caught and bowled for seven with the Tigers on 27. Earlier, England, who resumed on 374-3, finally ended their run-feat 40 minutes before the tea break. Skipper Alistair Cook extended his overnight 158 to a career-best 173 before the left-hander was eventually caught and bowled by Mahmudullah to leave the tourists in a commanding position of 487-4 at lunch. He struck 16 fours and two sixes in his 283-ball knock. Then England vice-captain Paul Collingwood and Ian Bell then combined to take game away from the hosts with a 184-run stand for the fifth wicket. Collingwood was eventually out for 145 and his partner Bell (84) fell three runs later allowing Cook to dec
